The erroneous code fails because the variable lacks an initial value before printing. You must assign a value to the variable before using it in any operation.

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

This corrected version initializes the variable with a string literal. The next class will assign a new value to this same variable.

```java
public class AssignValue {
    public static void updateVariable(String variable) {
        variable = "New value assigned";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The following class demonstrates how to concatenate the variable with another string.

```java
public class ConcatenateString {
    public static void concatenateVariable(String variable) {
        String result = variable + " and more text";
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
```

The final class compares the variable against another string and returns the result of that comparison.

```java
public class CompareString {
    public static boolean compareVariable(String variable) {
        String target = "Hello world";
        return variable.equals(target);
    }
}
```

All four classes now work together to manage and manipulate the original variable without any syntax errors.
